=== Mental Health Survey Clustering Analysis ===

Introduction

This project focuses on applying machine learning techniques to analyze a mental health survey dataset from tech industry employees. The goal of this project is to uncover potential clusters within the data to identify groups of employees with similar mental health challenges or needs. The problem is approached as an unsupervised clustering task, with the objective of providing insights into workplace mental health patterns that can help improve organizational support structures. The dataset includes a variety of features related to mental health, demographics, work environment, and attitudes towards mental health at the workplace. This analysis aims to explore latent patterns, visualize the data, and evaluate the quality of clusters identified by several clustering algorithms. In this project, I analyzed an openly accessible dataset on Kaggle that was called Mental Health in Tech Survey which was initially gathered by Open Sourcing Mental Illness (OSMI) in 2014.

The project was structured into four main tasks:

Task 1: Data preprocessing and exploration
Task 2: Application of multiple clustering algorithms
Task 3: Evaluation, visualization, and finalization of the best clustering model
Task 4: Reflection on results, interpretability, and ethical implications

== Task 1. Data Understanding & Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) ==

The dataset includes answers to one of the mental health surveys that were carried out among employees of the tech industry. It consists of demographic data, information about work, and questions connected with mental health. This is aimed at identifying potential groupings in the respondents based on clustering since the problem is un-supervised.

1.7 Imputing Missing Values

In[32]:
df['Age'] = df['Age'].fillna(df['Age'].median())

cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(include='object').columns
for col in cat_cols:
    if df[col].isnull().sum() > 0:
        df[col] = df[col].fillna(df[col].mode()[0])

print("\nMissing values after imputation:", df.isnull().sum().sum())

Missing values after imputation: 0

Explanation: In the case of the numerical column Age, I used the median as a value, to fill the missing values, since it is less affected by extreme values in the samples, such as mean. In a categorical column I had replaced the missing value by the mode (most frequently occurring value) with the thinking that the most common category would serve as a decent replacement. I ensured that all the missing values were filled after imputation.

2.3 Preprocessing: Scaling and Encoding Features

In[40]:
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', StandardScaler(), num_cols),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(drop='if_binary', sparse_output=False, handle_unknown='ignore'), cat_cols)
    ]
)

X_proc = preprocessor.fit_transform(X)
print("Shape after preprocessing:", X_proc.shape)

Shape after preprocessing: (1258, 58)

Explanation: I took the numerical features to the unit variance and placed them at zero by applying StandardScaler. This helps favorably to the many machine learning algorithms. I used the one-hot-encoding method to transform categories into binary columns with a categorical variable. I chose the option of dropping one column in encoder : in case the category is binary to avoid redundancy. Now the preistsed dataset X_proc can be clustered.

2.6 Clustering Algorithms

To explore different groupings within the data, I applied and compared five clustering algorithms using scikit-learn: KMeans, Agglomerative Clustering, DBSCAN, Birch, and Spectral Clustering. These models were selected for their varied approaches to partitioning and discovering hidden patterns in data:

KMeans Uses centroid-based partitioning and is efficient for spherical clusters.

Agglomerative Clustering A hierarchical method that builds nested clusters by merging or splitting.

DBSCAN Groups together closely packed points and identifies outliers as noise.

Birch Optimized for large datasets with noise; constructs a tree of clusters incrementally.

Spectral Clustering Captures non-convex clusters using graph theory based on similarity matrices.

I trained each model on the preprocessed feature matrix (X_proc). DBSCAN dynamically determined the number of clusters based on density, while the others used a fixed n_clusters=3 for comparability. Each model's clustering performance was assessed using:

Silhouette Score Measures how well a point fits within its cluster (higher is better).

Davies-Bouldin Index Measures intra-cluster similarity and inter-cluster differences (lower is better).

In[43]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, AgglomerativeClustering, DBSCAN, Birch, SpectralClustering
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score, davies_bouldin_score

clustering_models = {
    'KMeans': KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42, n_init=10),
    'Agglomerative': AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3),
    'DBSCAN': DBSCAN(eps=2, min_samples=5),
    'Birch': Birch(n_clusters=3),
    'Spectral': SpectralClustering(n_clusters=3, assign_labels='discretize', affinity='nearest_neighbors', random_state=42, n_neighbors=10)
}

cluster_results = {}

for name, model in clustering_models.items():
    labels = model.fit_predict(X_proc)
    n_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0) if name == 'DBSCAN' else len(set(labels))
    sil = silhouette_score(X_proc, labels) if n_clusters > 1 else None
    db = davies_bouldin_score(X_proc, labels) if n_clusters > 1 else None
    
    cluster_results[name] = {
        'labels': labels,
        'n_clusters': n_clusters,
        'silhouette': sil,
        'davies_bouldin': db
    }

    # Plotting
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
    plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=labels, cmap='tab10', alpha=0.5)
    plt.title(f'{name} Clustering on PCA Projection')
    plt.xlabel('PC1')
    plt.ylabel('PC2')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Explanation: I used five clustering algorithms namely KMeans, AgglomerativeClustering, DBSCAN, Birch, and SpectralClustering. To assess the quality of cluster I have computed the Silhouette Score and Davies-Bouldin Score. I also compared the results of the clustering since I projected the data into the two major components of PCA.

3: Evaluation & Error Analysis

In this section, I evaluated the clustering performance both quantitatively and qualitatively, and reflected on potential limitations and sources of error.

3.1 Quantitative Evaluation of Cluster Quality

To assess the quality of the clusters generated by each algorithm, I used two widely accepted internal clustering metrics:

Silhouette Score: Measures how similar each sample is to its own cluster versus other clusters. A higher score indicates well-defined clusters.

Davies-Bouldin Index: Evaluates the average "similarity" between clusters. Lower values suggest better separation.

3.5 Model Tuning / Improvements

In order to maximize KMeans clustering model, I used a variety of number of clusters (k) between 2-7. As the evaluation measure, the silhouette score was applied as it evaluates the degree to which clusters are well-separated. This tuning assists in determining the most suitable number of clusters to distribute uniformity across clusters and separation of one cluster to another.

In[49]:
# Tune KMeans by testing different k values
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

sil_scores = []
ks = range(2, 8)
for k in ks:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    labels = km.fit_predict(X_proc)
    sil = silhouette_score(X_proc, labels)
    sil_scores.append(sil)

# Plot the results
plt.plot(ks, sil_scores, marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.title('KMeans Tuning: Silhouette Score vs k')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print("Silhouette scores for different k:", dict(zip(ks, sil_scores)))

Silhouette scores for different k: {2: 0.12808801444963222, 3: 0.13167029637000352, 4: 0.08420232287041272, 5: 0.07522225450775248, 6: 0.06503719035849878, 7: 0.07044502049514043}

The silhouette scores that are plotted show the sensitivity with which the quality of clusters changes under various values of k. Based on the observation, k= 3 had a large silhouette score, which affirmed that it was the best number of clusters to use in this data. This is in line with previous results and it confirms the choice of three clusters that are to be analysed finally.

Such cluster labels may be used downstream, e.g. in the interpretation of the group characteristics, visual inspection, or as input to a recommender and monitoring system.

4: Reflection

4.1 Interpretation of Results

The above findings using clustering analysis indicate that the tech industry employees might be very well assorted into three groups according to their responses with regards to mental health. These categories have been formed with the help of such considerations as previous diagnoses, attitudes to finding help, a support system at work, and readiness to seek help. The internal clustering scores (Silhouette Score, Davies-Bouldin Index) were not very high, as it is normal when the data reflects subjective or social sciences aspects, yet the KMeans model using three clusters identified some valuable and practical patterns.

Practically, it means that in various organizations, similar clustering can be applied with the purpose to single out the groups of employees who may be more vulnerable to mental conditions, or those who are less likely to address the problem. The specified insights might be very useful to the HR departments, as they would be able to implement specific mental health support systems or awareness initiatives or educate the managers, which would contribute to a more inclusive and supportive workplace in the end.

4.2 Why the Model Makes Certain Predictions

Unsupervised clustering models such as KMeans would not directly provide prediction but we can still find a post-hoc explanation on the reason as to why the model grouped the employees as it did by examining the feature distributions that we had during the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA). Some of the characteristics that must have swayed the clusters are:

Family history of mental illness:

This could have led to grouping individuals who had the history of mental illnesses in families into a group of their own.

Lack of willingness to ask for help:

Individuals who did not feel free asking their employer to help them may have been put in the same cluster.

Access to work-related mental health resources:

Employees who responded to having access to such resources as mental health programs or counseling probably made up a group.

Comfort level when discussing mental health issues with supervisors:

Those who were comfortable with discussing with their managers on their mental health problems were likely to belong to a different bracket than the rest who were not.

Such characteristics are essential when considering the frontiers between the groups. By way of example, individuals with strong support systems, no past or family history of mental illness, and those open to discussing mental health in general, may have been lumped in one cluster more than those who have experienced support obstacles, family mental illness history, and so on.

4.3 Fairness and Ethical Considerations

It is important to remember that mental health is a heavily touchy subject, so one must be careful with the information and the conclusions. Yet, the data has been anonymized, but there is still the possibility of a bias:

Under-representation of some cohorts:

In case the minorities or individuals, who are not willing to reveal their mental well-being status, did not participate in the poll, the clusters will not promote the whole population.

Self-selection bias:

Individuals who have made a decision to complete the survey can be more open to the discussion of mental health, which causes a biasness in the results.

Overinterpretation of clusters:

Unsupervised models, such as those under clustering (e.g. KMeans) merely group the data based on their similarity with one another, but they do not provide any causality. Such groupings are not supposed to result to decision making without carrying further ethical reviews.

Since this clustering must produce results that are fair, it should not be allowed to determine the hiring and promoting of people based on said result unless a more thorough review of the ethics are conducted. The utilization of any such models should ensure the preservation of privacy and a lack of support of mental health stigma.

4.4 Model Interpretability

Compared to other models, such as DBSCAN or Spectral Clustering that might be more difficult to interpret, KMeans appeared comparatively easy to interpret. KMeans operates through the process of creating centroids (the means based on the values) of all the clusters which makes it simpler to comprehend the way of forming the groups. Nevertheless, the KMeans algorithm does not present the data clearly, so it is possible to consider the cluster centers as the ways to calculate the common values of variables describing the group.

To demonstrate further, I applied the Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to display the data in a two-dimension form. This enabled me to graphically examine the clusters as well as have a look at the characteristics that added to the differentiation between groups. Though KMeans is easy to understand and interpret, I would advise researching other alternatives such as SHAP or t-SNE in case we would like to explore more about feature importance.

4.5 Limitations and Future Work

Although the clustering analysis was a useful method of knowledge provision, a couple of limitations ought to be noted:

Cluster quality:

Silhouette score and Davies-Bouldin score were not so good, which means that the selected features might not reflect the patterns in data completely. This is an indication that the data may not in nature provide the perfect clusters, or the selected features were not ideal in this kind of work.

Lack of diversity in data:

There is a lack of diversity of the data set used as it is comprised mostly of responses given by persons residing in North America so the outcomes cannot readily be depicted in a worldwide populace.

Absence of external validation:

The external sources, such as the expert labels or follow-up surveys, were not used to validate the clusters and this complicates the ability to verify that the clusters can be of any practical interest.

In future I would:

Add some other characteristics (the size of the company, the occupation, or benefits at work), which could provide better findings on the perceptions of mental health and its control in the workplace.

Apply such advanced techniques as PCA to facilitate the interpretation or even consider alternative clustering algorithms as Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM) or Self-organizing Maps (SOM).

In order to make sure that the groupings done reflect the real needs of mental health in the workplace, clusters should be validated externally (according to expert opinion or employee opinion).

4.6 Summary of Reflection

This was a useful project about how clustering models could be utilized in mental health data of employees. With the help of the KMeans and Agglomerative Clustering, I managed to discover valuable trends and groupings that can be used in the organizational strategies. These models performed quite well, yet I have discovered some areas of enhancement, primarily concerning the enrichment of a dataset and fine-tuning the models.

The principles emphasized in relation to ethical concerns, including the aspects of fairness and privacy, were considered an essential part of the procedure, and I took care not to leave unaddressed the possible bias of the data. Regardless of the performance on clustering, the limitations of the given project, including the absence of labeled data to validate it and the possibility of under-representation of some groups, indicate that additional efforts will produce more realistic and practical findings.

This consideration illustrates the reasoning required of working with machine learning models, particularly on touchy matters like mental health among employees. The project can be also improved by studying more features, more advanced methods, and by conducting a better performance measure.
